In May 2006, Maradona agreed to take part in UK's Soccer Aid (a program to raise money for UNICEF).[213] In September 2006, Maradona, in his famous blue and white number 10, was the captain for Argentina in a three-day World Cup of Indoor Football tournament in Spain. On 26 August 2006, it was announced that Maradona was quitting his position in the club Boca Juniors because of disagreements with the AFA, who selected Alfio Basile to be the new coach of the Argentina national team.[214] In 2008, Serbian filmmaker Emir Kusturica made Maradona, a documentary about Maradona's life.[215]
